  "prompt": "Which is the best book for SQL?",
  "response": "There are several excellent books for learning SQL, depending on your skill level and specific needs. Here are some top recommendations:\n\nFor Beginners:\n1. \"SQL QuickStart Guide\" by Walter Shields\n- Easy to understand\n- Great for absolute beginners\n- Practical examples\n\n2. \"Head First SQL\" by Lynn Beighley\n- Visual learning approach\n- Beginner-friendly\n- Engaging and interactive\n\nFor Intermediate Learners:\n1. \"SQL Queries for Mere Mortals\" by John L. Viescas\n- Comprehensive explanations\n- Practical scenarios\n- Suitable for those with basic knowledge\n\n2. \"Learning SQL\" by Alan Beaulieu\n- Covers multiple database systems\n- Clear explanations\n- Good for hands-on learning\n\nAdvanced/Professional:\n1. \"SQL Performance Tuning\" by Grant Fritchey\n- Advanced optimization techniques\n- In-depth performance analysis\n- Recommended for database professionals\n\n2. \"T-SQL Fundamentals\" by Itzik Ben-Gan\n- Microsoft SQL Server focused\n- Advanced techniques\n- Detailed explanations\n\nOnline Resources:\n- W3Schools SQL Tutorial\n- Mode Analytics SQL Tutorial\n- SQLZoo\n\nChoose based on your current skill level and specific learning goals.",
